artery","Left internal carotid artery","Left ophthalmic artery","Central retinal artery"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft brachiocephalic artery\u003C/strong\u003E is not involved in the arterial blood supply to the left eye because it does not exist. The brachiocephalic artery is only present on the right side of the body, where it gives rise to the right common carotid and right subclavian arteries. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe blood supply to the left eye involves the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft common carotid artery\u003C/strong\u003E, which branches into the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft internal carotid artery\u003C/strong\u003E, and subsequently the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft ophthalmic artery\u003C/strong\u003E. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral retinal artery\u003C/strong\u003E is a branch of the ophthalmic artery that supplies the retina.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The blood supply to each eye comes from the ophthalmic artery, which branches from the internal carotid artery on the same side.","The arterial pathway to each eye is: common carotid \u2192 internal carotid \u2192 ophthalmic artery.","The brachiocephalic artery only exists on the right side of the body, giving rise to the right common carotid and right subclavian arteries."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Bird B, Stawicki SP. Anatomy, Head and Neck, Ophthalmic Arteries. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29493942.","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63321"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16344"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63321"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T10:55:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T21:47:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9035"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77802"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":